You are writing TypeScript. The goal of types is to make bugs impossible at compile time, not to satisfy the compiler with the minimum effort. Use types to encode real constraints about your domain.

## Strictness First

Always use strict mode. In `tsconfig.json`:

```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strict": true,           // enables all strict checks
    "noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true,  // arr[0] is T | undefined, not T
    "exactOptionalPropertyTypes": true, // { a?: string } ≠ { a: string | undefined }
    "noImplicitReturns": true,
    "noFallthroughCasesInSwitch": true
  }
}
```

Never use `// @ts-ignore` or `// @ts-nocheck`. Fix the type error properly.

## Type Design

### Prefer specific types over broad ones

```typescript
// 🚨 Too broad — accepts anything
function process(data: any) {}
function process(data: object) {}
function process(id: string) {} // is it a UUID? a slug? an email?

// ✅ Specific and self-documenting
function process(data: UserRecord) {}
type UserId = string & { readonly __brand: 'UserId' }
function getUser(id: UserId) {}
```

### Use union types to model real states

```typescript
// 🚨 Allows impossible states — what if loading=true and error is set?
interface State {
  loading: boolean
  data: User | null
  error: Error | null
}

// ✅ Only valid states are representable
type State =
  | { status: 'idle' }
  | { status: 'loading' }
  | { status: 'success'; data: User }
  | { status: 'error'; error: Error }
```

### Use `unknown` instead of `any` for truly unknown data

```typescript
// 🚨 any bypasses all type checking
function parseConfig(raw: any) {
  return raw.port // no error even if port doesn't exist
}

// ✅ unknown forces you to validate before using
function parseConfig(raw: unknown): Config {
  if (!isConfig(raw)) throw new Error('Invalid config')
  return raw // now narrowed to Config
}
```

### Narrow types explicitly

```typescript
// Type guards
function isUser(value: unknown): value is User {
  return (
    typeof value === 'object' &&
    value !== null &&
    'id' in value &&
    'email' in value
  )
}

// Discriminated unions (prefer over type guards when possible)
function handleState(state: State) {
  switch (state.status) {
    case 'loading': return <Spinner />
    case 'success': return <UserCard user={state.data} /> // data is User here
    case 'error': return <Error message={state.error.message} />
  }
}
```

## Common Patterns

### Generic functions

```typescript
// ✅ Generic preserves the specific type
function first<T>(arr: T[]): T | undefined {
  return arr[0]
}

const name = first(['alice', 'bob']) // string | undefined, not any
```

### Utility types

```typescript
// Use built-in utility types
type UserPreview = Pick<User, 'id' | 'name' | 'avatar'>
type UserUpdate = Partial<Pick<User, 'name' | 'email' | 'bio'>>
type ReadonlyUser = Readonly<User>

// Derive types from runtime values — single source of truth
const ROLES = ['admin', 'editor', 'viewer'] as const
type Role = typeof ROLES[number] // 'admin' | 'editor' | 'viewer'

const config = { port: 3000, host: 'localhost' } as const
type Config = typeof config
```

### Async types

```typescript
// Always type Promise results
async function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<User> { ... }

// Use Result type for operations that can fail
type Result<T, E = Error> =
  | { ok: true; value: T }
  | { ok: false; error: E }

async function safeParseJson(text: string): Promise<Result<unknown>> {
  try {
    return { ok: true, value: JSON.parse(text) }
  } catch (e) {
    return { ok: false, error: e as Error }
  }
}
```

## What NOT to Do

```typescript
// ❌ Casting instead of fixing
const user = response as User         // doesn't validate, just lies to compiler
const el = document.getElementById('app') as HTMLDivElement // crashes if null

// ✅ Validate or handle null properly
const el = document.getElementById('app')
if (!(el instanceof HTMLDivElement)) throw new Error('Missing #app element')

// ❌ Unnecessary non-null assertion
const name = user!.profile!.name  // crashes at runtime if any are null

// ✅ Handle nullability
const name = user?.profile?.name ?? 'Anonymous'

// ❌ Enums (they compile to unexpected JS)
enum Direction { Up, Down }

// ✅ Const object or union type
const Direction = { Up: 'up', Down: 'down' } as const
type Direction = typeof Direction[keyof typeof Direction]
```

## Type Error Fixes

When you see a type error:
1. Read the full error message — TypeScript tells you exactly what's wrong
2. Don't cast to `any` — understand why the types don't match
3. The error is usually at the call site, but the fix is often in the type definition
4. If two things should be the same type, make them share a type definition
